<DOC><DOCNO> AP881027-0132 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 1439EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-GMRecall     10-27 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-GM Recall,180</SECOND><HEAD>Vehicles Recalled to Replace Defective Switch</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. has begun recalling nearly750,000 1984-model cars and trucks bearing Chevrolet, Pontiac andGMC nameplates to replace a defective switch in the pollutioncontrol system, the Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday.   The action brings to 2.4 million the number of GM cars and trucksfrom the 1982, 1983 and 1984 model years recalled to install newthermal vacuum switches, which control emissions during warmup. Adefective switch can cause excessive emissions of carbon monoxideand unburned gasoline.   Models affected are the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic,Camaro, Monte Carlo and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville,Grand Prix and Parisienne and the GMC Caballero. They are equippedwith 3.8-liter (231 cubic inches) six-cylinder and 5.0-liter (305cubic inches) and 5.7-liter (350 cubic inches) V-8 engines.   Of the 749,802 vehicles being recalled, 53,114 were sold inCalifornia, which has separate standards from the rest of thecountry and sometimes is not affected by recalls.   Recall letters ask owners to schedule appointments with dealersfor free replacements, EPA said.</TEXT></DOC>